<br>
=================<br>
I will agree that, in order to refute your hard evidence, I should provide hard evidence of my own. In the case where there is a lack of hard evidence, I do not feel compelled to follow your gut over mine.<br>
=================<br>
<br>
Not at all unreasonable.<br>
<br>
=================<br>
For your first point, I am ... direct nuke and rain spells.<br>
=================<br>
<br>
In the same vein as your point above, I am not prepared to put too much <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>relative</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> credance on the figures for another class casting their own spells of a different type, compared to my own detailed study for mage rain spells using Sirocco. Hopefully, at some time in the future, I or another Archmage will find the time to perform a study into the resist rates on DDs and/or Bolts for these 61+ Mage spells in actual hunting situations. In the absence of such a study, however, although as I said I would suggest a figure of 17.5%, a modified figure of 20% is also not unreasonable.<br>
<br>
=================<br>
For your second point, I again challenge your testing. BoT, like all places where you fight large creatures, is an exception to the general bolts-in-fighting rule. Any time your target's Z-center is above the heads of your melee, you will have a difficult time missing with bolts. <br>
=================<br>
<br>
You make a good point here, regarding the Z-axis. And this is one of the key ways that the experienced evocationalist ensures that all or very close to all bolts hit. Make sure all melee are given shrink if at all possible. Sit on a horse. Cast levitation on yourself (I summon a bag full of lev rings every time I log in). Use any geography in the hunting area to your advantage (e.g. stand on any nearby rocks). Do any and every thing you can to get elevation and angle over the heads of the melee. Make sure the group know not to 'wall' mobs or fight in tight junctions/doorways. And, when you are soloing or small group hunting, pick your hunting grounds, choose to hunt in places that are to your advantage with bolts. Really, there is so much the evocationalist can do to massively stack those odds in her favour, all it takes is thought and dedication. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
=================<br>
It is also not entirely reasonable to expect every mage to yell at their groups until they behave ...<br>
=================<br>
<br>
Now, this is a more sensitive issue, I agree. It is something I do. I talk to any groupmembers who block bolts by their carelessness or who 'wall' mobs needlessly, explaining the impact of such on the group DPS (and hence the XP rate). I have found the single largest cause of lost bolts is not melee, however, but casters - clerics, druids, chanters, wizards etc, who wander around, often for little reason, during xp grinds and block bolts in the process, especially if they are on horseback. They are a minority of players, but I come across them from time to time. But really, most good players can be educated very quickly. All of my regular groupmates are becoming good at this now, and I rarely ever lose even a single bolt to any of them anymore. The only way for them to learn, however, is to tell them. It is not usually hard to persuade casters to watch where they stand, when they can see how much faster the xp comes along when they do. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
=================<br>
, or dismount and get into PB range.<br>
=================<br>
<br>
This is not my usual or preferred tactic, although I imagine some might use it. I usually only do this for mini-raids with 2-3 groups fighting smaller mobs, or if for some reason I am hunting in areas I usually avoid for XP-ing, like in tighter areas where there is little room, where even the tactics described above are not foolproof. It does, I admit, have its limitations.<br>
<br>
=================<br>
What it comes down to is that I haven't seen any good evidence in any way suggesting what a reasonable mitigation number for bolts is<br>
=================<br>
<br>
Another good point. I shall have to think about a good way to test this.<br>
<br>
=================<br>
There are many tactics that can be used to mitigate these misses, some easier than others. My initial intent was to represent the case where only the most minimal of those tactics were taken. (I loathe the melee-range tactic because it forces me to dismount... call me lazy if you will  )<br>
=================<br>
<br>
Yes, I gave such a list of tactics above. But I *do* understand laziness, it is the best reason you could give for not bothering, we all sometimes do not want to do the 'extra work', and want to be lazy. And I can only agree, achieving 98%+ bolts hitting home does take a lot more work and skill than just pressing that DD button. Some players, however, use this as justification for saying that DDs are simply better and/or higher DPS/DPM, and if they do, then they are mistaken.<br>
<br>
=================<br>
My question for you, Suzanna: Keeping in mind the chart is intended as a tool for the average mage (you obviously don't need the help), what would you replace my numbers with, and why? <br>
=================<br>
<br>
This is another good point, in that you explain your purpose in setting the mitigation values as you do. However, your graphs are not being used in this way. I came to this post because two seperate conjuration magi on my server (one a good friend of mine) claimed that these graphs 'proved' that the DPM/DPS of the top conjure nukes were better than is achievable with FoT, which immediately drew my analytical interest. Examination of the maths showed the opposite to be true if the mage has some skill and experience in using bolts.<br>
<br>
So to answer your question, I would use 17.5% (though I accept 20% as not unreasonable) and 2.0% (which is what I think I could achieve on average in the places I XP, using the tactics I employ).<br>
<br>
And my question to you in reply is: whilst your figures might have relevance to the 'average' mage (whatever that is exactly), why aim at the 'average' mage at all? Aim at what can be achieved by someone who gains the skill. I am not in any way special, and if I can do it, so can every other mage who practices (if they want to, of course). And I am quite sure, there are many <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>evocationalist</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> magi especially out there who already get far lower miss rates on bolts than 10%.<br>
<br>
Seriously, this has been a good discussion, sir, I thank you <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
/bow<br>
